reviewText:
Who doesn't like cars? From a beautiful Ford Mustang, to a luxury Bentley or even an eco-friendly model. Everyone likes cars, unless they don't. And being part of that gang, I thought it would be a good idea to try out this new game, and share my experience with the world.

It's a never ending battle of making your cars better and also trying to be better yourself.


Dale Earnhardt

Without any further delay, I present to you my review of Car Mechanic Simulator 2015.

GameplayFirst of all, let me tell you something. This game will screw you with the amount of screws you'll have to unscrew and rescrew during your mechanic career.
As a garage owner, your objective is, as in any other game, to make money, which will be used to upgrade that same garage, as well as to buy parts for other cars, and even to buy cars.
After accepting the first job, there's a list that tells the player what's wrong with said car, and, obviously, it's up to the player to open up that car and find those parts, and replace or repair them. If you choose to replace, you can just order the piece you need online, however, if you choose to repair the piece, you'll save money, or you’ll end up breaking it.
As the game goes on, and the player gains experience, which can be used to get some scanners and faster tools, those lists indicating the problem will cease to exist, and it will be up to the player to use everything available to find the problem and fix it. Plan B, which let me tell you, always works, is simply to dismantle the entire car and check every single piece, but that does take quite a while, as you can imagine.
I didn't know the difference between a spark plug and a crankshaft, but now I do! So fear not if you don't know anything about the mechanical side of cars, or even anything related to cars, because you'll learn it all.
Car Mechanic Simulator 2015 will bring out the mechanic in you that you never knew existed. Trust me, I'm (now) a mechanic.

Pros Incredible details;
Plenty of pieces, from rubber bushings to spark plugs, CMS2015 has it all;
The difficulty ladder is really well designed, and the player won't feel a difference when the harder repairs come by, if anything, it will feel easier with all the practice;
Some interesting tools available to help discover what needs to be fixed, from testing paths, to electronic meters, there's a nice variety to use and abuse;
Intuitive job objectives that help the player to find out where the problem is, without having to dismantle the entire car (even though that's the fun part!);
Nice variety of cars, with more being added in the future;
No game has as many screws as CMS2015;
The auction house allows the player to buy a (almost) ruined car and resell it, after it has been worked a bit, for profit.
I wouldn't be surprised to see some of the Cons" listed below improved in future patches/updates
